<section xml:id="review-graphing-lines">

    <title>Graphing Lines Chapter Review</title>

    <subsection>
        <title>Review of Cartesian Coordinates</title>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Cartesian Coordinate System</title>
            <p>The Cartesian coordinate system identifies the location of every point in a plane with an ordered pair.</p>
        </paragraphs>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>On paper, sketch a Cartesian coordinate system with units, and then plot the following points: <m>(3,2),(-5,-1),(0,-3),(4,0)</m>.</p>

                <sidebyside widths="47%">
                    <image>
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[]
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3, 2)} node[above] {$(3,2)$};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-5, -1)} node[below] {$(-5,-1)$};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0, -3)} node[right] {$(0,-3)$};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(4, 0)} node[above] {$(4,0)$};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </sidebyside>
            </statement>
        </example>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Review of Graphing Equations</title>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Graphing Equations</title>
            <p>To graph an equation with two variables <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>, we can choose some reasonable <m>x</m>-values, then calculate the corresponding <m>y</m>-values, and then plot the <m>(x,y)</m>-pairs as points. For many (not-so-complicated) algebraic equations, connecting those points with a smooth curve will produce an excellent graph.</p>
        </paragraphs>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Graph the equation <m>y=-2x+5</m>.</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Making a table for <m>y=-2x+5</m></caption>
                    <sidebyside margins="0%">
                        <table>
                        <caption>Set up the table</caption>
                        <tabular valign="top" bottom="minor">
                            <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                            <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                            <col halign="center"/>
                            <row bottom="medium">
                                <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>y=-2x+5</m></cell>
                                <cell>Point</cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>\phantom{-2(-2)+5=\substitute{9}}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>\phantom{(-2,9)}</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>\phantom{-2(-1)+5=\substitute{7}}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>\phantom{(-1,7)}</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>\phantom{-2(0)+5=\substitute{5}}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>\phantom{(0,5)}</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>\phantom{-2(1)+5=\substitute{3}}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>\phantom{(1,3)}</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row bottom="none">
                                <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>\phantom{-2(2)+5=\substitute{1}}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>\phantom{(2,1)}</m></cell>
                            </row>
                        </tabular>
                    </table>
                    <table>
                        <caption>Complete the table</caption>
                        <tabular valign="top" bottom="minor">
                            <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                            <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                            <col halign="center"/>
                            <row bottom="medium">
                                <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>y=-2x+5</m></cell>
                                <cell>Point</cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>-2(-2)+5=\substitute{9}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>(-2,9)</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>-2(-1)+5=\substitute{7}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>(-1,7)</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>-2(0)+5=\substitute{5}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>(0,5)</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>-2(1)+5=\substitute{3}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>(1,3)</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row bottom="none">
                                <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>-2(2)+5=\substitute{1}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>(2,1)</m></cell>
                            </row>
                        </tabular>
                        </table>
                    </sidebyside>
                </figure>

                <p>We use points from the table to graph the equation. First, plot each point carefully. Then, connect the points with a smooth curve. Here, the curve is a straight line. Lastly, we can communicate that the graph extends further by sketching arrows on both ends of the line.</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Graphing the Equation <m>y=-2x+5</m></caption>
                    <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
                        <figure>
                        <caption>Use points from the table</caption>
                        <image>
                            <description>a Cartesian grid with points (-2,9),(-1,7),(0,5),(1,3),(2,1)</description>
                            <latex-image>
                                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-1,ymax=10,
                                                xtick=,
                                                minor xtick=,
                                                ytick=,
                                                minor ytick=,]
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,9)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(-2,9)$};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1,7)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(-1,7)$};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,5)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(0,5)$};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1,3)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(1,3)$};;
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,1)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(2,1)$};;
                                    \end{axis}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                                ]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                    <figure>
                        <caption>Connect the points in whatever pattern is apparent</caption>
                        <image>
                            <description>a Cartesian grid with points (-2,9),(-1,7),(0,5),(1,3),(2,1)</description>
                            <latex-image>
                                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-1,ymax=10,
                                                xtick=,
                                                minor xtick=,
                                                ytick=,
                                                minor ytick=,]
                                        \addplot+[domain=-2.5:3] {-2*x+5};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,9)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(-2,9)$};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1,7)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(-1,7)$};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,5)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(0,5)$};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1,3)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(1,3)$};;
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,1)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(2,1)$};;
                                    \end{axis}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                                ]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                        </figure>
                    </sidebyside>
                </figure>
            </statement>
        </example>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Review of Two-Variable Data and Rate of Change</title>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Exploring Two-Variable Data and Rate of Change</title>
            <p>For a linear relationship, by its data in a table, we can see the rate of change (slope) and the line's <m>y</m>-intercept, thus writing the equation.</p>
        </paragraphs>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Write an equation in the form <m>y=\ldots</m> suggested by the pattern in the table.</p>

                <sidebyside>
                    <tabular >
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-4</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-6</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-8</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-10</m></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </sidebyside>

                <p>We consider how the values change from one row to the next. From row to row, the <m>x</m>-value increases by <m>1</m>. Also, the <m>y</m>-value decreases by <m>2</m> from row to row.</p>

                <sidebyside>
                    <tabular >
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell />
                            <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                            <cell />
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell />
                            <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-4</m></cell>
                            <cell />
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>{}+1\rightarrow</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-6</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\leftarrow{}-2</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>{}+1\rightarrow</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-8</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\leftarrow{}-2</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>{}+1\rightarrow</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-10</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\leftarrow{}-2</m></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </sidebyside>

                <p>Since row-to-row change is always <m>1</m> for <m>x</m> and is always <m>-2</m> for <m>y</m>, the rate of change from one row to another row is always the same: <m>-2</m> units of <m>y</m> for every <m>1</m> unit of <m>x</m>.</p>

                <p>We know that the output for <m>x = 0</m> is <m>y = -4</m>. And our observation about the constant rate of change tells us that if we increase the input by <m>x</m> units from <m>0</m>, the ouput should decrease by <m>\overbrace{(-2)+(-2)+\cdots+(-2)}^{x\text{ times}}</m>, which is <m>-2x</m>. So the output would be <m>-4-2x</m>.</p>

                <p>So the equation is <m>y=-2x-4</m>.</p>
            </statement>
        </example>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Review of Slope</title>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Slope</title>
            <p>When <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are two variables where the rate of change between any two points is always the same, we call this common rate of change the <term>slope</term>. Since having a constant rate of change means the graph will be a straight line, it's also called the <term>slope of the line</term>.</p>
        </paragraphs>

        <p>We can find a line's slope by drawing a slope-triangle on the line's graph, and then using the formula<men>m=\frac{\text{change in $y$}}{\text{change in $x$}}=\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}</men></p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Find the slope of the line in the following graph.</p>

                <sidebyside widths="47%">
                    <image>
                        <description>This is a grid with a line, passing the points (3,15) and (6,27). A slope triangle is drawn, starting at (3,15), passing (6,15), and ends at (6,27). The label from (3,15) to (6,15) is "6-3=3"; the label from (6,15) to (6,27) is "27-15=12".</description>
                        <latex-image>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[xlabel={x},
                                        ylabel={y},
                                        xmin=-1,xmax=9,
                                        ymin=-3,ymax=30,
                                        minor ytick=,
                                        minor xtick=,
                                        xtick={},
                                        ytick={},
                                        clip=false]
                                \addplot+[domain = 1:6.5]{4*x+3};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3, 15)} node[above left] {$(3,15)$};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(6, 27)} node[above left] {$(6,27)$};
                                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(3,15) (6,15)} node[pos=0.5,below,align=left] {$6-3$\\${}=3$};
                                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(6,15) (6,27)} node[pos=0.5,below,rotate=90,align=left] {$27-15$\\${}=12$};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </sidebyside>

                <p>We picked two points on the line, and then drew a slope triangle. Next, we will do:<me>\text{slope}=\frac{12}{3}=4</me>The line's slope is <m>4</m>.</p>
            </statement>
        </example>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Finding a Line's Slope by the Slope Formula</title>
                <p>If we know two points on a line, we can find its slope without graphing and, instead, using the slope formula <m>\text{slope}=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</m></p>
            </paragraphs>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Example</title>
                <p>A line passes the points <m>(-5,25)</m> and <m>(4,-2)\text{.}</m> Find this line's slope.<md>
                        <mrow>\text{slope}\amp=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=\frac{-2-(25)}{4-(-5)}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=\frac{-27}{9}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=-3</mrow>
                    </md>The line's slope is <m>-3</m>.
                </p>
            </paragraphs>
        </sidebyside>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Review of Slope-Intercept Form</title>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Graphing a Line in Slope-Intercept Form</title>

            <p>A line's equation in slope-intercept form looks like <m>y=mx+b</m>, where <m>m</m> is the line's slope, and <m>b</m> is the line's <m>y</m>-intercept.</p>

            <p>We can use a line's <m>y</m>-intercept and slope triangles to graph it.</p>
        </paragraphs>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Graph the line <m>y=-\frac{2}{3}x+10</m>.</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Graphing <m>y=-\frac{2}{3}x+10</m></caption>
                    <sidebyside widths="32% 32% 32%" margins="0%">
                    <figure>
                        <caption>First, plot the line's <m>y</m>-intercept, <m>(0,10)</m>.</caption>
                        <image>
                            <description></description>
                            <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[ymin=0,ymax=20,
                                                ytick={0,5,...,20},
                                                y axis line style = {->},
                                                minor ytick={0,1,...,20}]
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,10)} node[above right] {$(0,10)$};
                                    \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                    <figure>
                        <caption>The slope is <m>-\frac{2}{3}=\frac{-2}{3}=\frac{2}{-3}</m>. So we can try using a <q>run</q> of <m>3</m> and a <q>rise</q> of <m>-2</m> or a <q>run</q> of <m>-3</m> and a <q>rise</q> of <m>2</m>.</caption>
                        <image>
                            <description></description>
                            <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[ymin=0,ymax=20,
                                                ytick={0,5,...,20},
                                                y axis line style = {->},
                                                minor ytick={0,1,...,20}]
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,10)};
                                        \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,10) (3,10) (3,8)};
                                        \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(3,8) (6,8) (6,6)};
                                        \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,10) (-3,10) (-3,12)};
                                        \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(-3,12) (-6,12) (-6,14)};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3,8)} node[below left] {$(3,8)$};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(6,6)} node[below left] {$(6,6)$};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-3,12)} node[above right] {$(-3,12)$};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-6,14)} node[above right] {$(-6,14)$};
                                    \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                    <figure>
                        <caption>Arrowheads and labels are encouraged.</caption>
                        <image>
                            <description></description>
                            <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[ymin=0,ymax=20,
                                                ytick={0,5,...,20},
                                                y axis line style = {->},
                                                minor ytick={0,1,...,20}]
                                        \addplot+[domain=-7:7] {-2/3*x+10} node[pos=0.6,sloped,above] {$y=-\frac{2}{3}x+10$};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,10)};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3,8)};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(6,6)};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-3,12)};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-6,14)};
                                    \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                    </sidebyside>
                </figure>
            </statement>
        </example>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Writing a Line's Equation in Slope-Intercept Form Based on Graph</title>

            <p>Given a line's graph, we can identify its <m>y</m>-intercept, and then find its slope by a slope triangle. With a line's slope and <m>y</m>-intercept, we can write its equation in the form of <m>y=mx+b</m>.</p>
        </paragraphs>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Find the equation of the line in the graph.</p>
                <figure>
                    <caption>Find the equation of the line in the graph.</caption>
                    <sidebyside widths="32% 32% 32%" margins="0%">
                    <figure>
                        <caption>Graph of a line</caption>
                        <image>
                            <description></description>
                            <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[ymin=0,ymax=20,
                                                ytick={0,5,...,20},
                                                y axis line style = {->},
                                                minor ytick={0,1,...,20}]
                                        \addplot+[domain=-7:7] {-2/3*x+10};
                                    \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                    <figure>
                        <caption>Identify the line's <m>y</m>-intercept, <m>10</m>.</caption>
                        <image>
                            <description></description>
                            <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[ymin=0,ymax=20,
                                                ytick={0,5,...,20},
                                                y axis line style = {->},
                                                minor ytick={0,1,...,20}]
                                        \addplot+[domain=-7:7] {-2/3*x+10};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,10)} node[right] {$(0,10)$};
                                    \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                    <figure>
                        <caption>Identify the line's slope by a slope triangle. Note that we can pick any two points on the line to create a slope triangle. We would get the same slope: <m>-\frac{2}{3}</m></caption>
                        <image>
                            <description></description>
                            <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[ymin=0,ymax=20,
                                                ytick={0,5,15,20},
                                                y axis line style = {->},
                                                minor ytick={0,1,...,20}]
                                        \addplot+[domain=-7:7] {-2/3*x+10};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,10)};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3,8)} node[below] {$(3,8)$};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-3,12)} node[above] {$(-3,12)$};
                                        \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,10) (3,10)} node[pos=0.5,above,align=center] {$3$};
                                        \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(3,10) (3,8)} node[pos=0.5,right,align=center] {$-2$};
                                        \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(-3,10) (0,10)} node[pos=0.5,below,align=center] {$3$};
                                        \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(-3,10) (-3,12)} node[pos=0.5,left,align=center] {$-2$};
                                    \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                        </figure>
                    </sidebyside>
                </figure>
                <p>With the line's slope <m>-\frac{2}{3}</m> and <m>y</m>-intercept <m>10</m>, we can write the line's equation in slope-intercept form: <m>y=-\frac{2}{3}x+10</m>.</p>
            </statement>
        </example>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Review of Point-Slope Form</title>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Point-Slope Form</title>

            <p>A line's point-slope form equation is in the form of <m>y=m\left(x-x_0\right)+y_0</m>, where <m>m</m> is the line's slope, and <m>(x_0,y_0)</m> is a point on the line.</p>
        </paragraphs>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>A line passes through <m>(-6,0)</m> and <m>(9,-10)\text{.}</m> Find this line's equation in both point-slope and slope-intercept form.</p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p>We will use the <xref ref="equation-slope-formula" text="title">slope formula</xref> to find the slope first. After labeling those two points as <m>(\overset{x_1}{-6},\overset{y_1}{0}) \text{ and } (\overset{x_2}{9},\overset{y_2}{-10})\text{,}</m> we have:<md>
                    <mrow>\text{slope}\amp=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{-10-0}{9-(-6)}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{-10}{15}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=-\frac{2}{3}</mrow>
                </md></p>

                <p>Now the point-slope equation looks like <m>y=-\frac{2}{3}(x-x_0)+y_0\text{.}</m> Next, we will use <m>(9,-10)</m> and substitute <m>x_0</m> with <m>9</m> and <m>y_0</m> with <m>-10\text{,}</m> and we have:<md>
                    <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}(x-x_0)+y_0</mrow>
                    <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}(x-9)+(-10)</mrow>
                    <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}(x-9)-10</mrow>
                </md></p>

                <p>Next, we will change the point-slope equation into slope-intercept form:<md>
                        <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}(x-9)-10</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}x+6-10</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}x-4</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

    </subsection>



    <subsection>
        <title>Review of Standard Form</title>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Standard Form</title>

            <p>A line's equation in standard form looks like <m>Ax+By=C</m>. We need to convert a line's equation from standard form to slope-intercept form, and vice versa.</p>
        </paragraphs>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
            <paragraphs>
                <p>Converting from Standard Form to Slope-Intercept Form</p>
            </paragraphs>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Examples</title>
                <p>Convert <m>2x+3y=6</m> into slope-intercept form.<md>
                        <mrow>2x+3y\amp=6</mrow>
                        <mrow>2x+3y\subtractright{2x}\amp=6\subtractright{2x}</mrow>
                        <mrow>3y\amp=-2x+6</mrow>
                        <mrow>\divideunder{3y}{3}\amp=\divideunder{-2x+6}{3}</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=\frac{-2x}{3}+\frac{6}{3}</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}x+2</mrow>
                    </md>The line's equation in slope-intercept form is <m>y=-\frac{2}{3}x+2</m>.
                </p>
            </paragraphs>
        </sidebyside>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
            <paragraphs>
                <p>Converting from Slope-Intercept Form to Standard Form</p>
            </paragraphs>
            <paragraphs>
                <p>Convert <m>y=-\frac{2}{3}x+2</m> into standard form.<md>
                        <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}x+2</mrow>
                        <mrow>\multiplyleft{3}y\amp=\multiplyleft{3}(-\frac{2}{3}x+2)</mrow>
                        <mrow>3y\amp=3\cdot(-\frac{2}{3}x)+3\cdot2</mrow>
                        <mrow>3y\amp=-2x+6</mrow>
                        <mrow>3y\addright{2x}\amp=-2x+6\addright{2x}</mrow>
                        <mrow>2x+3y\amp=6</mrow>
                    </md>The line's equation in standard form is <m>2x+3y=6</m>.
                </p>
            </paragraphs>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>To graph a line in standard form, we could first change it to slope-intercept form, and then graph the line by its <m>y</m>-intercept and slope triangles. A second method is to graph the line by its <m>x</m>-intercept and <m>y</m>-intercept.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Graph <m>2x-3y=-6</m> using its intercepts. And then use the intercepts to calculate the line's slope.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We calculate the line's <m>x</m>-intercept by substituting <m>y=0</m> into the equation<md>
                    <mrow>2x-3y\amp=-6</mrow>
                    <mrow>2x-3(\substitute{0})\amp=-6</mrow>
                    <mrow>2x\amp=-6</mrow>
                    <mrow>x\amp=-3</mrow>
                </md>So the line's <m>x</m>-intercept is <m>(-3,0)\text{.}</m></p>

                <p>Similarly, we substitute <m>x=0</m> into the equation to calculate the <m>y</m>-intercept:<md>
                    <mrow>2x-3y\amp=-6</mrow>
                    <mrow>2(\substitute{0})-3y\amp=-6</mrow>
                    <mrow>-3y\amp=-6</mrow>
                    <mrow>y\amp=2</mrow>
                </md>So the line's <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>(0,2)</m>.</p>

                <p>With both intercepts' coordinates, we can graph the line:</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Graph of <m>2x-3y=-6</m></caption>
                    <image width="47%">
                    <description>This is a grid with the graph of line 2x-3y=-6. The following points are plotted: (0,2), (-3,0). The segment from (0,0) to (0,2) is labeled "2-0=0", and the segment from (-3,0) to (0,0) is labeled "0-(-3)=3".</description>
                    <latex-image>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[xmin=-5,xmax=2,
                                        ymin=-1,ymax=4,
                                        minor xtick=,
                                        minor ytick=,
                                        xtick={-4,-3,...,1},
                                        ytick={1,2,3}]
                                \addplot+[domain=-4.5:2]{2/3*x+2};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0, 2)} node[above left] {$(0,2)$};;
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-3, 0)} node[above left] {$(-3,0)$};
                            \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    ]]>
                    </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Review of Horizontal, Vertical, Parallel, and Perpendicular Lines</title>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Horizontal, Vertical, Parallel, and Perpendicular Lines</title>

            <p>A horizontal line's equation looks like <m>y=k</m>, while a vertical line's equation looks like <m>x=h</m>. The following figure has graphs of a horizontal line and a vertical line.</p>
        </paragraphs>

        <figure>
            <caption>Graphs of <m>y=3</m> and <m>x=5</m></caption>
            <image width="50%">
            <description>a horizontal line at y=3 and a vertical line at x=5</description>
            <latex-image>
                <![CDATA[
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}
                        \addplot[primarycurve]{3} node[pos=0.6,above,align=center] {$y=3$};
                        \addplot[primarycurve,blue] coordinates {(5,-7) (5,7)} node[pos=0.6,left,align=center,blue] {$x=5$};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
            </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Parallel and Perpendicular Lines</title>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
            <paragraphs>
                <p>Two lines are parallel if and only if they have the same slope.</p>
            </paragraphs>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Examples</title>
                <p>Line <m>m</m>'s equation is <m>y=-2x+20</m>. Line <m>n</m> is parallel to <m>m</m>, and line <m>n</m> also passes the point <m>(4,-3)</m>. Find line <m>n</m>'s equation.</p>
                <p>Since parallel lines have the same slope, line <m>n</m>'s slope is also <m>-2</m>. Since line <m>n</m> also passes the point <m>(4,-3)</m>, we can write line <m>n</m>'s equation in point-slope form:<md>
                        <mrow>y\amp=m(x-x_1)+y_1</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=-2(x-4)+(-3)</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=-2(x-4)-3</mrow>
                    </md>We can also easily get the line's equation in slope-intercept form:<md>
                        <mrow>y\amp=-2(x-4)-3</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=-2x+8-3</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=-2x+5</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </paragraphs>
        </sidebyside>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
            <paragraphs>
                <p>Two lines are perpendicular if and only if the product of their slopes is <m>-1</m>.</p>
            </paragraphs>
            <paragraphs>
                <p>Line <m>m</m>'s equation is <m>y=-2x+20</m>. Line <m>n</m> is perpendicular to <m>m</m>, and line <m>n</m> also passes the point <m>(4,-3)</m>. Find line <m>n</m>'s equation.</p>
                <p>Since line <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> are perpendicular, the product of their slopes is <m>-1</m>. Because line <m>m</m>'s slope is given as <m>-2</m>, we can find line <m>n</m>'s slope is <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.</p>
                <p>Since line <m>n</m> also passes the point <m>(4,-3)</m>, we can write line <m>n</m>'s equation in point-slope form:<md>
                        <mrow>y\amp=m(x-x_1)+y_1</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=\frac{1}{2}(x-4)+(-3)</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=\frac{1}{2}(x-4)-3</mrow>
                    </md>We can also easily get the line's equation in slope-intercept form:<md>
                        <mrow>y\amp=\frac{1}{2}(x-4)-3</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=\frac{1}{2}x-2-4</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=\frac{1}{2}x-6</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </paragraphs>
        </sidebyside>
        </paragraphs>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Review of Linear Inequalities in Two Variables</title>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Linear Inequalities in Two Variables</title>

            <p>When we graph lines like <m>y=2x+1</m>, we are graphing points which satisfy the relationship <m>y=2x+1</m>, like <m>(0,1), (1,3), (2,5)</m>, etc. Similarly, we can graph linear inequalities like <m>y\gt2x+1</m> by plotting all points which satisfies the inequality, like <m>(0,2), (0,3), (1,4), (1,5)</m>, etc. All these points form a region, instead of a line.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Graph <m>y\gt2x+1\text{.}</m></p>
                <p>There are two steps to graph an inequality.<ol>
                    <li>Graph the line <m>y=2x+1\text{.}</m> Because the inequality symbol is <m>\gt\text{,}</m> (instead of <m>\ge</m>) the line should be dashed (instead of solid).</li>
                    <li>Next, we need to decide whether to shade the region above <m>y=2x+1</m> or below it. We will choose a point to test whether <m>y\gt2x+1</m> is true. As long as the line doesn't cross <m>(0,0)\text{,}</m> we will use <m>(0,0)</m> to test, because the number <m>0</m> is the easiest number for calculation.<md>
                        <mrow>y\gt2x+1</mrow>
                        <mrow>0\stackrel{?}{\gt}2(0)+1</mrow>
                        <mrow>0\stackrel{?}{\gt}1</mrow>
                    </md>Because <m>0\gt1</m> is not true, the point <m>(0,0)</m> is not a solution and should not be shaded. As a result, we shade the region without <m>(0,0)\text{.}</m>
                    </li></ol>
                </p>

                <sidebyside widths="45% 45%">
                    <figure>
                        <caption>Step 1 of graphing <m>y\gt2x+1</m></caption>
                        <image>
                        <description>This is a coordinate plane with y=2x+1 graphed.</description>
                        <latex-image>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[
                                    xmin=-5,xmax=5,ymin=-5,ymax=5,
                                    minor xtick=, minor ytick=,
                                    xtick={-4,-3,...,4},ytick={-4,-3,...,4}
                                ]
                                    \addplot[
                                        domain = -3:2,
                                        <->,
                                        dashed,
                                        thin,
                                        color = red,
                                    ]{2*x+1};
                                \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>

                    <figure>
                        <caption>Step 2 of graphing <m>y\gt2x+1</m></caption>
                        <image>
                        <description>This is a coordinate plane with y=2x+1 graphed. The region above the line is shaded.</description>
                        <latex-image>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[
                                    xmin=-5,xmax=5,ymin=-5,ymax=5,
                                    minor xtick=, minor ytick=,
                                    xtick={-4,-3,...,4},ytick={-4,-3,...,4}
                                ]
                                    \addplot[
                                        domain = -3:2,
                                        <->,
                                        dashed,
                                        thin,
                                        color = red,
                                    ]{2*x+1};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0, 0)} node[above right] {test point: $(0,0)$};

                                    \draw [color=blue,dotted] (axis cs: -4.5,-5) -- (axis cs: -4.5, 5);
                                    \draw [color=blue,dotted] (axis cs: -4,-5) -- (axis cs: -4, 5);
                                    \draw [color=blue,dotted] (axis cs: -3.5,-5) -- (axis cs: -3.5, 5);
                                    \draw [color=blue,dotted] (axis cs: -3,-5) -- (axis cs: -3, 5);
                                    \draw [color=blue,dotted] (axis cs: -2.5,-2*2.5+1) -- (axis cs: -2.5, 5);
                                    \draw [color=blue,dotted] (axis cs: -2,-2*2+1) -- (axis cs: -2, 5);
                                    \draw [color=blue,dotted] (axis cs: -1.5,-2*1.5+1) -- (axis cs: -1.5, 5);
                                    \draw [color=blue,dotted] (axis cs: -1,-2+1) -- (axis cs: -1, 5);
                                    \draw [color=blue,dotted] (axis cs: -0.5,-2*0.5+1) -- (axis cs: -0.5, 5);
                                    \draw [color=blue,dotted] (axis cs: 0,1) -- (axis cs: 0, 5);
                                    \draw [color=blue,dotted] (axis cs: 0.5,2*0.5+1) -- (axis cs: 0.5, 5);
                                    \draw [color=blue,dotted] (axis cs: 1,2*1+1) -- (axis cs: 1, 5);
                                    \draw [color=blue,dotted] (axis cs: 1.5,2*1.5+1) -- (axis cs: 1.5, 5);
                                \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </sidebyside>
            </statement>
        </example>
        </paragraphs>

    </subsection>

